{
  "id": "numbers",
  "order": 1,
  "title": {
    "en": "Numbers",
    "uz": "Sonlar"
  },
  "icon": "🔢",
  "blurb": "Count to a thousand with a dozen building blocks",
  "quiz": "counting",
  "article": [
    {
      "heading": "Numbers that play fair",
      "body": [
        "If you have ever fought with French *quatre-vingt-dix* or German *einundzwanzig*, Uzbek numbers will feel like a holiday. They are **completely regular** — no special words for eleven or twelve, no swapping the order of the digits. Learn the units, the tens, plus **yuz** (hundred) and **ming** (thousand), and you can say every number up to 9,999.",
        "The rule is simply: say the parts **biggest first**, in a row, with a space between them. No joining words, no exceptions."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "o'n besh",
          "english": "fifteen (ten + five)",
          "breakdown": [
            "o'n",
            "besh"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "ten",
            "five"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "yigirma bir",
          "english": "twenty-one (twenty + one)",
          "breakdown": [
            "yigirma",
            "bir"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "twenty",
            "one"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "The tens, then hundreds and thousands",
      "body": [
        "The tens each have their own word: **yigirma** 20, **o'ttiz** 30, **qirq** 40, **ellik** 50, **oltmish** 60, **yetmish** 70, **sakson** 80, **to'qson** 90. After that it is just **yuz** (100) and **ming** (1,000).",
        "One handy quirk: a lone hundred or thousand drops the **bir**. 100 is just **yuz**, not *bir yuz*; 1,000 is just **ming**. But 200 is **ikki yuz** and 2,000 is **ikki ming**."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "uzbek": "ikki yuz qirq besh",
          "english": "245 (two hundred forty-five)",
          "breakdown": [
            "ikki",
            "yuz",
            "qirq",
            "besh"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "two",
            "hundred",
            "forty",
            "five"
          ]
        },
        {
          "uzbek": "o'n ming so'm",
          "english": "10,000 som — a common banknote",
          "breakdown": [
            "o'n",
            "ming",
            "so'm"
          ],
          "gloss": [
            "ten",
            "thousand",
            "som"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Why it matters",
      "body": [
        "Prices in Uzbekistan run into the thousands of som, so the words **ming** and **yuz** do a lot of heavy lifting at the bazaar. Get comfortable hearing *o'ttiz ming* (30,000) and *ellik ming* (50,000) and haggling gets a great deal easier."
      ]
    }
  ],
